	<pb facs="liv_002343_0001" n="0001"/><!-- Change both @facs and @n -->
	<!-- Start each page with a <pb> formatted as above -->

<!-- If this is a letter or similar with an opener (with content such as dateline and/or salute) add it. For example: -->

<opener>
<lb/><dateline rend="right"><add place="above" rend="right" hand="U">70</add><placeName><placeName>Burnbank Road</placeName> 
<lb/><add place="marginleft" hand="U">Acc. 912.</add> <placeName>Hamilton</placeName></placeName> <date when="1865-06-20">20 June
<lb/>1865</date></dateline>
<lb/>    
<lb/><salute>My Dear Brother</salute>
</opener>

<lb/><p>I have to give 
<lb/>you the intimation
<lb/>of our mother's
<lb/>departure to a better
<lb/>world on <date when="1865-06-18">Sunday
<lb/>the 18<hi rend="sup underline">th</hi> <choice><abbr>currt.</abbr><expan cert="medium">current</expan></choice></date> and
<lb/>beg you to <w>com -
<lb break="no"/>municate</w> the same
<lb/>to <persName>Neil</persName> and any
<lb/>other relatives at
<lb/>your convenience

	<pb facs="liv_002343_0002" n="0002"/>
<lb/>She had been long
<lb/>confined to bed but
<lb/>an attack of <term type="ailment">Bronchitis</term>
<lb/>took away most
<lb/>of her remaining strength.
<lb/>She lingered for more
<lb/>than two months
<lb/>in excessive weakness
<lb/>&amp; <choice><sic>recieved</sic><corr>received</corr></choice> the 
<lb/>unremitting attention
<lb/>of <persName>Janet</persName> &amp; <persName>Agnes</persName>
<lb/>night &amp; day - <persName>Janet</persName>
<lb/>desires me to say
<lb/>that she would have
<lb/>written you long
<lb/>ago but could not.
<lb/>Mother was calm
<lb/>&amp; collected to the last

	<pb facs="liv_002343_0003" n="0003"/>
<lb/>When the changes came <add place="inline" rend="right" hand="#U">71</add>
<lb/>near <persName>Agnes</persName> said to
<lb/>her "<persName>Jesus</persName> is coming
<lb/>for you. Can you
<lb/>lippen to him." She
<lb/>replied "<quote>Yes.</quote>" - gave 
<lb/>her last look to
<lb/><persName>Anna Mary</persName> &amp; said
<lb/>"<quote>bonnie well lassie</quote>"
<lb/>&amp;fell asleep. She
<lb/>is to be buried
<lb/>beside Father on 
<lb/><date when="1865-06-22">22</date> or <date when="1865-06-23">23<hi rend="sup underline">d</hi></date></p>
<lb/><p>I was at <placeName><settlement type="city">Oxford</settlement></placeName>
<lb/>at the time. Left her
<lb/>a week ago better - 
<lb/>and she continued

	<pb facs="liv_002343_0004" n="0004"/>
<lb/>so till the change came. 
<lb/>A telegram called me
<lb/>away <date when="1865-06-19">yesterday</date>
<lb/>morning &amp; by travelling
<lb/>express I arrived
<lb/>this morning - and
<lb/>thank Him who
<lb/>after sparing her
<lb/>82 years has preserved
<lb/>her faithful to himself
<lb/>All the rest are well -
<lb/>No word of poor 
<lb/><persName>Robert</persName> - Give our
<lb/>love to all yours</p>

<closer rend="center">
<lb/><salute>Ever affectionately
<lb/>yours -</salute>
<lb/><signed><persName>David Livingstone</persName></signed><!-- There is a postal mark here. SF --> 
</closer>


